{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:09:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:09:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16936"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16936"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.82,0.01,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9626"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53292"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"670"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1325"},{"type":"tags","id":"2585"},{"type":"tags","id":"4128"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22710"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is reviewed on day two following a total laparoscopic hysterectomy for heavy menstrual bleeding. She complains of lower abdominal pain, urinary frequency, and fever. She has a medical history of hypertension and takes amlodipine. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with suprapubic tenderness. There is no discharge from her surgical wounds. A bladder scan reveals 800 mL of residual urine.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trial of void","Return to theatre for laparoscopy","Urinary catheterisation and antibiotics","Fluid challenge only","Urgent CT abdomen and pelvis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of urosepsis secondary to urinary retention following pelvic surgery. The combination of fever, tachycardia, hypotension, and significant post-void residual volume indicates the need for immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary catheterisation and antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. This addresses both the urinary retention and the likely urosepsis. Catheterisation provides immediate relief and allows for urine specimen collection, while empiric antibiotics should be commenced promptly given the signs of sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrial of void\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the large residual volume and signs of systemic infection. This could further delay appropriate treatment and worsen the patient\u0027s condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent CT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the first step. While imaging may be considered if the patient does not improve with initial management, the clinical picture is consistent with urinary retention and urosepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efluid challenge\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient. While fluid resuscitation is important in sepsis, it must be accompanied by source control (catheterisation) and antimicrobial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReturn to theatre\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the primary issue appears to be urinary retention with secondary infection rather than a surgical complication. There are no signs of wound infection or intra-abdominal collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-operative urinary retention is a common complication after pelvic surgery due to various factors including anaesthesia, pain, and surgical disruption of pelvic innervation. Early recognition and management is essential to prevent complications such as bladder overdistension injury and infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-operative urinary retention is a common complication after pelvic surgery and requires prompt catheterisation to prevent bladder overdistension.","Fever and urinary retention after gynaecological surgery should raise suspicion for urosepsis.","Empiric antibiotics should be commenced promptly in suspected urosepsis while awaiting culture results."],"references":["Wagenlehner FME, Pilatz A, Weidner W, Naber KG. Urosepsis: Overview of the Diagnostic and Treatment Challenges. Microbiol Spectr. 2015 Oct;3(5). doi: 10.1128/microbiolspec.UTI-0003-2012. PMID: 26542042."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53292"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16936"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53292"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T10:55:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T10:57:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9626"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67827"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu